{{about|early cinema|Bradford Brinton's collection of Indian art|Brinton Museum}}
The '''Brinton Collection''' is a collection of early [[cinematography]] which was used by William Franklin Brinton (July 12, 1857-Dec. 16, 1919) for his [[traveling show]] in the [[Midwestern United States]].   It was preserved by history teacher, Michael Zahs, in a barn in [[Ainsworth, Iowa]].  The collection includes works by [[Georges Méliès]] which were thought to have been lost: ''[[The Wonderful Rose-Tree]]'' and ''[[The Triple-headed Lady]]''.  The collection's history was recounted in a film documentary, ''[[Saving Brinton]]'' in 2017.<ref name=G/>

