{{eastern name order|Dr. Hiller István}}
Dr. '''István Hiller''' (born 7 May 1964 in [[Sopron]]) is a Hungarian politician and former chairman of the governing [[Hungarian Socialist Party]] between 16 October 2004 and 24 February 2007, succeeding [[László Kovács (politician)|László Kovács]], succeeded by [[Ferenc Gyurcsány]]. A co-founder of his party, Hiller was [[Minister of Culture]] under the government of [[Ferenc Gyurcsány]] from 2003 to 2005 before being replaced by [[András Bozóki]]. He became Vice chairman of the party in 2003. Hiller was the Minister of Education and Culture between 2006 and 2010. He was elected one of the [[List of Deputy Speakers of the National Assembly of Hungary|deputy speakers of the National Assembly]] in May 2014. In 2016, Hiller is elected caucus chair on the MSZP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mno.hu/belfold/tobias-vesztett-molnar-gyula-lett-az-mszp-uj-elnoke-1348972|title=Tóbiás vesztett, Molnár Gyula lett az MSZP új elnöke|last=KN|access-date=2016-06-25}}</ref>

Hiller attended university in [[Budapest]] and [[Heidelberg]], and carried out research at the [[University of Vienna]] in 1995 and 1997.
He speaks German, Latin and Ancient Greek fluently, as well as Italian and English.

==Personal life==
Hiller is married and has two sons, Gábor (b. 1990) and Dávid (b. 1992). His wife is Julianna Hillerné Farkas.<ref>[http://www.origo.hu/itthon/20030207hiller.html Hiller István vagyonnyilatkozata - 2003. február]</ref>

